==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*þegna-'', from Indo-European ''*tekno-'' ‘people born’, from ''*tek-'' ‘give birth, beget’.  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon [[thegan]] ‘man’, Old High German [[degan]] ‘boy, servant, hero’ (German [[Degen]] ‘warrior’), Old Norse [[þegn]] ‘freeman’.  The IE root was also the source of Greek [[τέκνον]] ‘child’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /θejn/

===Noun===
'''þeġn''' ''m'' (''pl'' '''þeġnas''')
# a [[thegn]] or [[thane]], a man holding lands from the king by military service, ranking above a freeman and below a hereditary nobleman

